<p class="story-body-text">Over the past year, at least three Hong Kong stores have stopped selling ivory after complaints by local conservationists. Stamps and decorative items made from ivory are traditionally valued in China, but in recent years activists have worked to highlight the connection between the sale of such products and the threatened extinction of African elephants.</p>
<p class="story-body-text">The Chinese basketball star Yao Ming is theÂ <a style="color: #326891;" href="http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/12/a-plea-to-shun-the-ivory-trade-from-yao-ming/">most visible face</a>Â of that campaign. He traveled to Africa in 2012 and recently released a book and documentary on the severe risks faced by elephants and rhinos due to poaching for their tusks and horns.</p>
<p class="story-body-text"><a title="Hong Kong" href="http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/29/conservationists-continue-push-to-block-hong-kong-ivory-sales/?src=twr&amp;_r=0" target="_blank">Read more.</a></p>


